---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const title = "Insurance for International Choreographers | Compare Expat Plans";
const description = "Health insurance guide for Choreographers working internationally, covering dance creation abroad, company commissions, touring productions, and choreographic career mobility.";
const headline = "Insurance for International Choreographers";
const subheadline = "Coverage solutions for Choreographers practicing abroad, creating dance works internationally, and building choreographic careers across global companies and venues.";
const canonicalPath = "/guides/choreographer-insurance";
const heroBackgroundImage = "/images/guides/choreographer-insurance-hero.png";

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', label: 'Overview' },
  { id: 'coverage-needs', label: 'Coverage Needs' },
  { id: 'work-settings', label: 'Work Settings' },
  { id: 'credentials', label: 'Credentials' },
  { id: 'occupational-health', label: 'Occupational Health' },
  { id: 'work-demands', label: 'Work Demands' },
  { id: 'career-considerations', label: 'Career Considerations' },
  { id: 'faqs', label: 'FAQs' },
  { id: 'next-steps', label: 'Next Steps' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title={title}
  description={description}
  headline={headline}
  subheadline={subheadline}
  canonicalPath={canonicalPath}
  heroBackgroundImage={heroBackgroundImage}
  tocItems={tocItems}
>
  <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">

    <section id="overview">
      <h2>International Choreographic Careers</h2>
      <p>
        Choreographers create movement and dance works, from concert dance to musical theater to commercial productions. They work with ballet companies, modern dance ensembles, musical productions, and independent projects. Choreography combines physical artistry with creative vision and leadership.
      </p>
      <p>
        International choreographic careers involve commissions from companies abroad, festival presentations, touring works, and residencies at foreign institutions. Dance is a global art form—choreographers work across national boundaries and cultural contexts. Understanding coverage for project-based creative work, physical demands, and international mobility is essential.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide addresses insurance considerations for Choreographers working abroad across ballet, modern dance, commercial, and independent settings.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="coverage-needs">
      <h2>Coverage Needs for Choreographers</h2>

      <ComparisonTable
        columns={[
          { key: 'need', header: 'Coverage Need' },
          { key: 'why', header: 'Why It Matters' },
          { key: 'typical', header: 'Coverage Situation?' },
        ]}
        rows={[
          { need: 'Musculoskeletal care', why: 'Physical demonstration and movement', typical: 'Usually covered' },
          { need: 'Travel medical', why: 'Commissions abroad, touring', typical: 'Varies by plan' },
          { need: 'Mental health support', why: 'Creative pressure, career stress', typical: 'Usually covered' },
          { need: 'Injury rehabilitation', why: 'Movement-related injuries', typical: 'Usually covered' },
          { need: 'Gap coverage', why: 'Between-project periods', typical: 'Self-arranged' },
          { need: 'Vision coverage', why: 'Visual spatial work', typical: 'Usually covered' },
        ]}
      />

      <h3>Project-Based Reality</h3>
      <p>
        Most choreographic work is project-based. Commissions are discrete engagements with specific companies. Coverage may exist during creation periods only. Freelance choreographers need individual coverage strategies.
      </p>
      <p>
        Some choreographers hold company positions—artistic director, resident choreographer. Company positions provide continuous coverage. But many successful choreographers work commission to commission. Coverage planning must address irregular employment.
      </p>

      <h3>Physical Involvement</h3>
      <p>
        Choreographers demonstrate movement during creation. Physical demands are significant even when not performing. Previous dance careers may have caused accumulated injuries. Coverage must address ongoing physical health needs.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-settings">
      <h2>Coverage by Work Setting</h2>

      <h3>Ballet Companies</h3>
      <p>
        Major ballet companies commission choreographers with professional contracts. Commission periods include coverage provisions. Residencies and repeated collaborations develop. Ballet company work offers well-structured engagements.
      </p>

      <h3>Modern Dance Companies</h3>
      <p>
        Modern dance companies vary significantly in resources. Major companies provide professional contracts. Smaller companies may have limited provisions. Coverage varies significantly across the modern dance field.
      </p>

      <h3>Musical Theater</h3>
      <p>
        Broadway and commercial musical choreography includes union coverage. Production contracts specify provisions. Commercial success provides ongoing opportunities. SDC membership affects contract terms.
      </p>

      <h3>Independent Work</h3>
      <p>
        Independent choreographers create work outside company structures. Grant funding may include coverage provisions. Self-produced work requires self-arranged coverage. Independent careers require careful coverage planning.
      </p>

      <h3>Academic Positions</h3>
      <p>
        University dance programs employ choreographers as faculty. Academic positions include institutional benefits. Teaching combines with creative work. Academic coverage provides stability.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Coverage for Choreographers"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for Choreographers working abroad across ballet, modern dance, and commercial settings."
      buttonText="Compare Choreography Plans"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

    <section id="credentials">
      <h2>Credentials and Professional Recognition</h2>

      <h3>Dance Background</h3>
      <p>
        Most choreographers have extensive dance training and performance experience. Dance careers inform choreographic practice. Physical understanding comes from embodied experience. Dance background is foundational.
      </p>

      <h3>Body of Work</h3>
      <p>
        Choreographic credentials come from created works. Commissions from recognized companies establish reputation. Critical attention and awards enhance standing. Portfolio of work determines opportunities.
      </p>

      <h3>Academic Training</h3>
      <p>
        MFA programs offer choreographic training. Academic credentials support teaching positions. Not all successful choreographers have formal degrees. Training complements practical experience.
      </p>

      <h3>Professional Networks</h3>
      <p>
        Dance networks connect choreographers with opportunities. Festival circuits provide visibility. Artistic director relationships determine commissions. Networks support career development globally.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="occupational-health">
      <h2>Occupational Health Considerations</h2>

      <h3>Physical Demands</h3>
      <p>
        Choreographers demonstrate movement constantly during creation. Physical demands continue even after performance careers. Accumulated injuries from dance careers persist. Coverage must address ongoing physical needs.
      </p>

      <h3>Accumulated Injuries</h3>
      <p>
        Dance careers create wear on bodies. Joint, muscle, and skeletal issues develop over time. Previous injuries require ongoing management. Coverage should address chronic and accumulated conditions.
      </p>

      <h3>Mental Health</h3>
      <p>
        Creative pressure is intense during creation periods. Rejection and competition affect wellbeing. Career uncertainty creates stress. Mental health coverage supports creative professionals.
      </p>

      <h3>Voice Health</h3>
      <p>
        Choreographers communicate constantly during rehearsals. Extended verbal direction strains voices. Studio acoustics may be poor. Voice care supports rehearsal demands.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-demands">
      <h2>Managing Work Demands</h2>

      <h3>Creation Intensity</h3>
      <p>
        Choreographic creation is intensive and consuming. Premiere deadlines are fixed. Multiple projects may overlap. Creation periods require focused energy.
      </p>

      <h3>Collaborative Demands</h3>
      <p>
        Choreography involves leading dancers and creative teams. Relationship management is constant. Company cultures vary significantly. Leadership stress accompanies creative work.
      </p>

      <h3>Career Uncertainty</h3>
      <p>
        Choreographic careers depend on continued commissions. Competition for opportunities is intense. Success doesn't guarantee future work. Career uncertainty creates ongoing stress.
      </p>

      <h3>Travel Demands</h3>
      <p>
        International careers require extensive travel. Time away from home for commissions is significant. Relationship and family strain occurs. Travel fatigue accumulates over time.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="career-considerations">
      <h2>Career Considerations</h2>

      <h3>International Opportunities</h3>
      <p>
        Dance is a global art form without language barriers. Companies worldwide commission choreographers. International experience enhances reputation. Coverage must accommodate global career possibilities.
      </p>

      <h3>Career Paths</h3>
      <p>
        Choreographic careers develop from performing backgrounds. Artistic director roles offer company leadership. Academic positions provide stability. Multiple paths exist for choreographic careers.
      </p>

      <h3>Physical Evolution</h3>
      <p>
        Choreographic practice evolves as bodies age. Demonstration becomes less intensive over careers. Movement direction replaces physical showing. Career sustainability requires adaptation.
      </p>

      <h3>Career Longevity</h3>
      <p>
        Choreographic careers can continue for decades. Senior choreographers remain productive into later years. Experience and vision deepen over time. Long-term career planning is feasible.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="faqs">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I have a commission abroad. What coverage applies?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Commission contracts should specify coverage provisions. Major companies typically provide commission-period insurance. Verify coverage before signing contracts. International commissions may have different provisions than domestic work.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I work commission to commission. How do I maintain coverage?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Project-based work creates coverage gaps. Individual international health insurance provides continuity. Union benefits may provide some gap coverage. Plan for coverage as part of career management.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">My dance career caused injuries that still affect me. What coverage addresses this?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Accumulated injuries from dance careers require ongoing care. Coverage should include musculoskeletal specialists. Physical therapy and rehabilitation help manage chronic issues. Address injuries proactively rather than ignoring them.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Creative pressure is affecting my mental health. What support exists?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Creative pressure is inherent to choreographic work. Use mental health coverage proactively. Therapists who understand creative professions exist. Develop sustainable practices for creation periods.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm touring a work internationally. What coverage do I need?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Touring requires travel medical coverage across multiple locations. Tour producers typically provide coverage. Verify coverage for all tour destinations. Individual coverage supplements tour provisions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I have an academic position. Is university coverage sufficient?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Academic positions typically provide comprehensive coverage. Verify coverage for professional work outside the university. Summer commissions and touring should be covered. Academic positions offer stable coverage for choreographers.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="next-steps">
      <h2>Next Steps</h2>
      <p>
        Start by understanding your coverage situation based on employment type. Commission-based choreographers need individual coverage strategies. Company positions provide stable coverage. Verify specific contract provisions for each engagement.
      </p>
      <p>
        Choreography creates movement art and advances dance culture. Your coverage should support this essential profession—enabling international career mobility, addressing physical demands, and providing continuity between creative projects.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Protect Your Choreographic Career"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for Choreographers working abroad across ballet, modern dance, and commercial settings."
      buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

  </article>
</PageShell>
